post_text: Congratulations Generations Hope! This student run organization has received a donation from Scheels The Colony.
shared_text:
Scheels (The Colony, TX)
September 14 at 9:55 PM ·

🌟SCHEELS North Texas Giving Day Recipient!🌟

Our fifth $1,500 recipient is Generations Hope!

Generations Hope was founded by 15 year old Lindsey, leading a youth group of volunteers who work together to bring memorable experiences and meaningful relationships to underprivileged youth living in multi-family residences. Known as the "Friday Night Club", this group allows a safe place for kids to gather, play, and pray.

To support Generations Hope, please follow the link to their donation page➡ https://www.northtexasgivingday.org/scheels/nonprofits?keyword=

post_text: Leadership Prep School is sponsoring a brick campaign to provide on-going support for the purchase of equipment, supplies, and other resources that contribute to the excellence of the computer-immersion and project-based learning programs for LPS students. 🧱 By purchasing a brick, you have the opportunity to have your child's name or family name engraved on a brick that will be installed in front of the Secondary Campus building.🧱 $75 includes 16 characters per line for up to three lines of engraving. post_text: As a New Tech Network school, Leadership Prep School has always focused on extensive planning, design, and implementation of project based learning. PBL is a pathway to develop problem solving, critical thinking and inter/intrapersonal competencies. This year, back to school planning has focused on innovation: testing collaborative technology, planning for digital team building, and even a sanitation demonstration by a biochemical expert. Read more about the benefits of PBL here: http://ow.ly/PuUB50AZ51S

post_text: We are so proud of 4th grader Julianne Jones! As she learned how families were being impacted by COVID, she was shocked that many were without food. She decided that day to host a food drive. She came up with a plan, asked her parents for help, and got a friend to help. She recorded a video to share on social media as well as friends and family. She collected food and donations for 2 days even going door to door in her neighborhood. She and her friend raised over $500 in food/donations and delivered it to Frisco Family Services. What a great example of leadership!!! Way to go, Julianne <3

LPS - you did a fantastic job raising money for sick and injured kids at Children's Hospital with our Day of Play program!

221 LPS students (K-12) raised $4,625 for Children's Hospitals during Day of Play!

Now on to our secondary student winners.

6th grade had the highest number of registered students, both by raw count and percentage of total enrollment, so we drew one 6th grade name for the XBOX...

The XBOX winner is...

Timothy B. (6th)

Congrats Timmy!

To encourage LPS families to share their pics and videos on the LPS facebook page, we had a special random drawing for those who posted there.

The winners are...

Gracie C. (5th) - Beats Headphones

Siri C. (5th) - Hover1 Hoverboard

The charts below show the individual awards for Most Dollars Raised, Most Donors Recruited, and Most Social Media Posts.

Your prizes will be included in your end of year bag on pick-up day.

Thanks to everyone who made our Day of Play a huge success!

post_text:
Secondary Student Families - We understand times are tough, but we also know you need some service hours. You can earn one hour just for creating a no-cost account with Extra-Life in an effort to raise awareness and money for Children’s Hospital. You will also receive one additional hour for every $10 raised. Remember to use #LPSDayOfPlay if you or your parents post your name and fundraising page link on social media for an opportunity to win prizes, like Beats headphones or a Hoverboard.
Even if you and your friends are not able to give, this is an excellent opportunity to build awareness for Children’s Hospital and the great work they do!

One of our 2nd graders is in an art contest and could use your votes! Manasvi's art was chosen and the final art selection is based on the number of votes secured.

Voting runs from 5/5-5/17. You can vote up to 10 times with the same email each day.

(The web page does not work very well on iPhone devices so you may want to switch to desktop version to vote.)

Thank you!

post_text: Secondary biology is on a virtual field trip! Mrs. Rice's class will be examining a variety of e-cigarette advertisements after watching the Be Vape Free virtual field trip- a real-world virtual learning opportunity to get the facts on the vaping epidemic. Students will gain powerful insights as several teenagers share their firsthand experiences of successfully avoiding e-cigarettes, learn how to think critically about everyday influences like advertising and social media, pick up effective refusal skills and debunk common myths with a health professional. Source: https://www.bevapefree.org/virtual-field-trip/

post_text:
Are you looking for a way to help neighbors and those in need during this coronavirus stuff?

One of our amazing freshman, Lindsey (age 14), started a non-profit outreach to the kids and families at the Budget Suites Motel in The Colony, TX. These families live there year round and are in need. Throughout the year Lindsey and her outreach, Generations Hope, serve with other teens and parents to provide meals, fun and hope on Friday nights.

During this time when grocery stores are running low and kids are out of school, they are providing more groceries and meals to the families.

You can contribute right from your home through the wishlist of needs they created on Amazon!

text:
Are you looking for a way to help neighbors and those in need during this coronavirus stuff?

One of our amazing freshman, Lindsey (age 14), started a non-profit outreach to the kids and families at the Budget Suites Motel in The Colony, TX. These families live there year round and are in need. Throughout the year Lindsey and her outreach, Generations Hope, serve with other teens and parents to provide meals, fun and hope on Friday nights.

During this time when grocery stores are running low and kids are out of school, they are providing more groceries and meals to the families.

You can contribute right from your home through the wishlist of needs they created on Amazon!

shared_text:
EVENTBRITE.COM
Freshman Info Night: Project Design & Analysis

UNT at Frisco
March 3 at 7:22 PM ·

In just three years, you will graduate with real work experience working alongside our community and corporate partners on innovative projects that matter!

Designed in a small group setting with high touch points with faculty and student support, this degree will give you the ability to confidently face the evolving tide of industry and societal need. With concentrations in Project Management, Design, and Operations Research and Analysis, you will enter the job market with highly sought-after skills and be prepared for a rewarding career path after graduation.

We invite you learn more about this program at one of our info sessions where you can speak directly with faculty and admissions officers.

Application Fee Waivers ($75) are available to all attendees!

Visit the program website here!

Email Dr. Hope Garcia at hope.garcia@unt.edu with any questions, or call 972.668.8114.

We look forward to meeting you!

post_text:
The Texas Match the Promise Foundation℠ encourages families to save for college by offering competitive matching scholarships and tuition grants to students who are beneficiaries of a Texas Tuition Promise Fund® account — the state's prepaid college tuition plan.

Match the Promise scholarships help young Texans realize their dreams of a college education while also encouraging families to take steps now to prepare for their children's futures.

To apply for a scholarship, the Promise Fund beneficiary must be in grade five through nine and have a family income of $100,000 or less. Students must write a career essay and meet residency and other requirements.

The Foundation accepts scholarship applications Sept. 1 through Dec. 31. Families also can enroll in the Promise Fund during the scholarship application period if they have not already done so.

Match the Promise is funded by generous contributions from citizens, building a stronger Texas for tomorrow.

https://comptroller.texas.gov/programs/education/match/
